{"id": "nsci-potassium-element-063", "type": "fact", "statement": "Potassium is a chemical element with symbol K and atomic number 19, an alkali metal essential for nerve and muscle function.", "explanation": "Potassium's symbol K comes from the Latin 'kalium,' derived from the Arabic word for plant ashes. It is the seventh most abundant element in Earth's crust. Potassium reacts violently with water, producing hydrogen gas and enough heat to ignite it with a characteristic lilac flame.", "wowFactor": "Drop potassium in water and it explodes with a purple flame!", "quizQuestion": "Why does potassium have the symbol K instead of P?", "correctAnswer": "K comes from the Latin 'kalium'", "distractors": [{"text": "P was already taken by phosphorus", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "K stands for its German name", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "It was a naming error", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "K is from the Greek word", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "Named after its discoverer Kaiser", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "K represents its crystal structure", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "It was randomly assigned", "difficultyTier": "easy"}], "variants": [{"question": "What color flame does potassium produce?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Lilac/Purple", "distractors": ["Green", "Red", "Orange"]}, {"question": "Which element reacts violently with water producing a purple flame?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Potassium", "distractors": ["Sodium", "Lithium", "Calcium"]}, {"question": "Potassium is NOT essential for which body function?", "type": "negative", "correctAnswer": "Bone growth", "distractors": ["Nerve signaling", "Muscle contraction", "Heart rhythm"]}, {"question": "Potassium's symbol K comes from the Latin _____.", "type": "fill_blank", "correctAnswer": "Kalium", "distractors": ["Krypton", "Kerium", "Kadmium"]}, {"question": "Potassium reacts violently with water.", "type": "true_false", "correctAnswer": "True",