{"id": "nsci-rhenium-element-072", "type": "fact", "statement": "Rhenium is a chemical element with symbol Re and atomic number 75, one of the rarest elements in Earth's crust.", "explanation": "Rhenium was the last stable element to be discovered, in 1925 in Germany. Named after the Rhine river, it has the third-highest melting point of all elements (3,186°C). Rhenium is primarily used in jet engine superalloys where extreme heat resistance is required.", "wowFactor": "Rhenium was the very last stable element discovered — scientists searched for it for decades!", "quizQuestion": "What is rhenium named after?", "correctAnswer": "The Rhine river", "distractors": [{"text": "A Roman emperor", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "The city of Rennes", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "A Greek god", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "Its discoverer Rhen", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "The Rhone river", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "A German university", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "The word 'rare'", "difficultyTier": "easy"}], "variants": [{"question": "What notable distinction does rhenium hold among stable elements?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Last to be discovered", "distractors": ["First to be discovered", "Most abundant", "Lightest"]}, {"question": "Which element has the third-highest melting point?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Rhenium", "distractors": ["Tungsten", "Osmium", "Iridium"]}, {"question": "Rhenium is NOT primarily used in which product?", "type": "negative", "correctAnswer": "Batteries", "distractors": ["Jet engines", "Superalloys", "Catalytic converters"]}, {"question": "Rhenium melts at over _____°C.", "type": "fill_blank", "correctAnswer": "3,000", "distractors": ["2,000", "4,000", "1,500"]}, {"question": "Rhenium was discovered in the 20th century.", "type": "true_false", "correctAnswer": "True", "distractors": ["False"]}], "difficulty": 4, "funScore": 6, "visualDescription": "A pixel art jet engine 