{"id": "nsci-lead-element-075", "type": "fact", "statement": "Lead is a chemical element with symbol Pb and atomic number 82, a dense metal known since antiquity that is toxic to humans.", "explanation": "Lead's symbol Pb comes from the Latin 'plumbum,' which also gives us the word 'plumber' (Romans used lead pipes). Lead was used in paint, gasoline, and water pipes for centuries before its toxicity was fully understood. The phaseout of leaded gasoline is linked to reduced crime rates worldwide.", "wowFactor": "The word 'plumber' literally comes from lead — Romans made water pipes from it!", "quizQuestion": "Where does lead's chemical symbol Pb come from?", "correctAnswer": "The Latin word 'plumbum'", "distractors": [{"text": "The Greek word 'plakos'", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "Its discoverer's name", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "The German word 'Blei'", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "An abbreviation of 'lead'", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "The Arabic word for heavy", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "The Celtic word for gray", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "A medieval Latin term", "difficultyTier": "medium"}], "variants": [{"question": "What English word derives from lead's Latin name?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Plumber", "distractors": ["Platinum", "Plutonium", "Plume"]}, {"question": "Which element was historically used in gasoline and paint?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Lead", "distractors": ["Mercury", "Arsenic", "Cadmium"]}, {"question": "Lead is NOT used in modern applications for which purpose?", "type": "negative", "correctAnswer": "Drinking water pipes", "distractors": ["Radiation shielding", "Car batteries", "Fishing weights"]}, {"question": "Lead's symbol Pb comes from the Latin _____.", "type": "fill_blank", "correctAnswer": "Plumbum", "distractors": ["Plutonium", "Palladium", "Platinum"]}, {"question": "The removal of lead from gasoline is linked to reduced crime rates.", "type": "true