{"id": "nsci-radium-element-076", "type": "fact", "statement": "Radium is a chemical element with symbol Ra and atomic number 88, famously discovered by Marie and Pierre Curie in 1898.", "explanation": "Radium was isolated from uranium ore by the Curies, who coined the term 'radioactivity.' It glows faintly blue in the dark due to its intense radioactivity. In the early 1900s, radium was added to clocks, toothpaste, and even drinking water before its dangers were understood. The tragic 'Radium Girls' who painted watch dials helped establish workplace safety laws.", "wowFactor": "People used to drink radium water as a health tonic — until they discovered it was killing them!", "quizQuestion": "Who discovered radium?", "correctAnswer": "Marie and Pierre Curie", "distractors": [{"text": "Ernest Rutherford", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "Niels Bohr", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "Henri Becquerel", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "Wilhelm Röntgen", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "Albert Einstein", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "Lise Meitner", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "Max Planck", "difficultyTier": "easy"}], "variants": [{"question": "What color does radium glow?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Blue", "distractors": ["Green", "Yellow", "Red"]}, {"question": "Which element was once added to toothpaste and drinking water?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Radium", "distractors": ["Fluorine", "Mercury", "Arsenic"]}, {"question": "Radium was NOT used in which early 1900s product?", "type": "negative", "correctAnswer": "Automobiles", "distractors": ["Clock dials", "Toothpaste", "Health tonics"]}, {"question": "The Curies coined the term _____ while studying radium.", "type": "fill_blank", "correctAnswer": "Radioactivity", "distractors": ["Radiation", "Nuclear fission", "Isotope"]}, {"question": "The 'Radium Girls' case helped establish workplace safety laws.", "type": "true_false", "correctAnswer": "True", "distractors":