{"id": "nsci-caesium-frequency-080", "type": "fact", "statement": "The second is defined by the unperturbed ground state hyperfine transition frequency of the caesium-133 atom, exactly 9,192,631,770 Hz.", "explanation": "Since 1967, the SI second has been defined by counting exactly 9,192,631,770 oscillations of radiation from a caesium-133 atom. This makes caesium atomic clocks the most precise timekeeping devices, accurate to within one second over 300 million years.", "wowFactor": "Caesium clocks are so accurate they won't lose a second in 300 million years!", "quizQuestion": "How many oscillations of caesium-133 define one second?", "correctAnswer": "9,192,631,770", "distractors": [{"text": "1,000,000,000", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "6,022,140,760", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "3,000,000,000", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "12,000,000,000", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "299,792,458", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "5,500,000,000", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "100,000,000", "difficultyTier": "easy"}], "variants": [{"question": "Which element defines the SI second?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Caesium-133", "distractors": ["Rubidium-87", "Hydrogen-1", "Strontium-88"]}, {"question": "Since what year has the second been defined by caesium?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "1967", "distractors": ["1955", "1983", "1950"]}, {"question": "Caesium atomic clocks are NOT used for which purpose?", "type": "negative", "correctAnswer": "Measuring temperature", "distractors": ["GPS satellites", "Defining the second", "Synchronizing networks"]}, {"question": "The SI second is defined by _____ oscillations of caesium-133.", "type": "fill_blank", "correctAnswer": "9,192,631,770", "distractors": ["299,792,458", "6,022,140,760", "1,000,000,000"]}, {"question": "Caesium atomic clocks are the basis for GPS timing.", "type": "true_false", "correctAnswer": "True", "distractors": ["False"]}], "difficulty": 4, "funScore": 7