{"id": "nsci-elementary-charge-082", "type": "fact", "statement": "The elementary charge is the electric charge carried by a single proton, approximately 1.602 × 10⁻¹⁹ coulombs.", "explanation": "The elementary charge is one of the fundamental constants of nature. It represents the smallest unit of free charge — all observable charges are integer multiples of it. Robert Millikan's famous oil-drop experiment in 1909 first measured it precisely. Since 2019, the coulomb is actually defined in terms of the elementary charge.", "wowFactor": "Every electric charge in the universe is an exact multiple of this one tiny number!", "quizQuestion": "What is the approximate value of the elementary charge?", "correctAnswer": "1.602 × 10⁻¹⁹ coulombs", "distractors": [{"text": "9.109 × 10⁻³¹ kg", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "6.626 × 10⁻³⁴ J·s", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "1.381 × 10⁻²³ J/K", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "3.14 × 10⁻¹⁰ C", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "9.8 × 10⁻⁵ C", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "2.998 × 10⁸ m/s", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "6.674 × 10⁻¹¹ N·m²/kg²", "difficultyTier": "hard"}], "variants": [{"question": "Who first precisely measured the elementary charge?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Robert Millikan", "distractors": ["J.J. Thomson", "Michael Faraday", "Benjamin Franklin"]}, {"question": "What experiment measured the elementary charge?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Oil-drop experiment", "distractors": ["Double-slit experiment", "Gold foil experiment", "Cavendish experiment"]}, {"question": "The elementary charge is NOT carried by which particle?", "type": "negative", "correctAnswer": "Neutron", "distractors": ["Proton", "Electron", "Positron"]}, {"question": "All observable charges are integer multiples of the _____ charge.", "type": "fill_blank", "correctAnswer": "Elementary", "distractors": ["Fundamental", "Primary", "Atomic"]}, {"question": "The elementary charge is the same magni