{"id": "nsci-seed-ball-092", "type": "fact", "statement": "A seed ball is a small sphere of clay mixed with seeds, compost, and sometimes chili powder, used for no-till reforestation.", "explanation": "Seed balls were popularized by Japanese farmer Masanobu Fukuoka as part of natural farming. The clay protects seeds from birds and harsh weather until rains soften it. Chili powder is sometimes added to deter animals. Seed balls have been used to reforest deserts and restore degraded landscapes by simply throwing them onto bare ground.", "wowFactor": "You can reforest a desert just by throwing clay balls stuffed with seeds — no digging required!", "quizQuestion": "Who popularized the modern seed ball technique?", "correctAnswer": "Masanobu Fukuoka", "distractors": [{"text": "Luther Burbank", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "Norman Borlaug", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "Gregor Mendel", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "Charles Darwin", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "Wangari Maathai", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "Johnny Appleseed", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "Rachel Carson", "difficultyTier": "medium"}], "variants": [{"question": "Why is chili powder sometimes added to seed balls?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "To deter animals from eating them", "distractors": ["To add nutrients", "To speed germination", "To attract pollinators"]}, {"question": "What protects the seeds inside a seed ball?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Clay coating", "distractors": ["Plastic wrap", "Wax layer", "Metal shell"]}, {"question": "Seed balls are NOT designed for which purpose?", "type": "negative", "correctAnswer": "Hydroponic farming", "distractors": ["Reforestation", "Desert restoration", "No-till agriculture"]}, {"question": "Seed balls soften when exposed to _____.", "type": "fill_blank", "correctAnswer": "Rain", "distractors": ["Sunlight", "Wind", "Frost"]}, {"question": "Seed balls are a form of no-till agriculture.", "type": "t