{"id": "nsci-admittance-vacuum-094", "type": "fact", "statement": "The admittance of vacuum is the reciprocal of the impedance of free space, approximately 1/377 siemens.", "explanation": "The admittance of vacuum describes how easily electromagnetic waves propagate through empty space. Its reciprocal, the impedance of free space (~377 ohms), determines how electric and magnetic fields relate in an electromagnetic wave. This value arises from the fundamental ratio of the permittivity and permeability of free space.", "wowFactor": "Empty space has electrical resistance — about 377 ohms — and it's the same everywhere in the universe!", "quizQuestion": "What is the approximate impedance of free space?", "correctAnswer": "377 ohms", "distractors": [{"text": "50 ohms", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "1000 ohms", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "100 ohms", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "0 ohms", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "75 ohms", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "500 ohms", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "1 ohm", "difficultyTier": "easy"}], "variants": [{"question": "What is admittance the reciprocal of?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Impedance", "distractors": ["Resistance", "Capacitance", "Inductance"]}, {"question": "What two properties of free space determine its impedance?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Permittivity and permeability", "distractors": ["Mass and charge", "Energy and frequency", "Voltage and current"]}, {"question": "The impedance of free space does NOT depend on which factor?", "type": "negative", "correctAnswer": "The observer's velocity", "distractors": ["Permittivity of free space", "Permeability of free space", "The speed of light"]}, {"question": "The impedance of free space is approximately _____ ohms.", "type": "fill_blank", "correctAnswer": "377", "distractors": ["50", "100", "1000"]}, {"question": "Empty space has a characteristic electromagnetic impedance.", "type": "true_false", "corre