{"id": "nsci-rubble-masonry-096", "type": "fact", "statement": "Rubble masonry is a construction technique using rough, uncut stones set in mortar, one of the oldest building methods still in use.", "explanation": "Rubble masonry has been used for thousands of years because it requires no stone cutting — builders simply fit irregularly shaped stones together with mortar. Ancient Roman walls, medieval castles, and many rural buildings worldwide use this technique. It remains popular in earthquake-prone regions because it flexes rather than shattering.", "wowFactor": "Some rubble masonry walls have stood for over 2,000 years — without a single cut stone!", "quizQuestion": "What distinguishes rubble masonry from dressed masonry?", "correctAnswer": "Rubble masonry uses rough, uncut stones", "distractors": [{"text": "Rubble masonry uses no mortar", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "Rubble masonry uses brick instead", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "Rubble masonry uses metal reinforcement", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "Rubble masonry is only for decoration", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "Rubble masonry requires precision tools", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "Rubble masonry uses concrete blocks", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "Rubble masonry is a modern invention", "difficultyTier": "easy"}], "variants": [{"question": "Which civilization extensively used rubble masonry?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Ancient Romans", "distractors": ["Ancient Egyptians (pyramids)", "Aztecs", "Chinese (Great Wall)"]}, {"question": "Why is rubble masonry suitable for earthquake zones?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "It flexes rather than shattering", "distractors": ["It's lighter than other methods", "It uses rubber mortar", "It's built underground"]}, {"question": "Rubble masonry does NOT require which tool?", "type": "negative", "correctAnswer": "Stone cutting saw", "distractors": ["Mortar trowel", "Level", "Plumb bob"]}, {"question": "