{"id": "nsci-brick-dust-097", "type": "fact", "statement": "Brick dust has been used as a construction additive for centuries, creating a hydraulic mortar that sets underwater.", "explanation": "When ground brick is mixed with lime mortar, it creates a pozzolanic reaction that allows the mortar to harden even when submerged in water. The Romans used crushed brick in their famous concrete, and it was widely used in canal and harbor construction before Portland cement was invented. Brick dust mortar can last for centuries.", "wowFactor": "Romans mixed crushed brick into their concrete — and those structures are still standing 2,000 years later!", "quizQuestion": "What special property does brick dust give to mortar?", "correctAnswer": "It can set and harden underwater", "distractors": [{"text": "It makes mortar red", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "It prevents freezing", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "It repels insects", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "It makes mortar elastic", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "It speeds drying time", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "It reduces weight", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "It adds fire resistance", "difficultyTier": "hard"}], "variants": [{"question": "What chemical reaction occurs when brick dust mixes with lime?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Pozzolanic reaction", "distractors": ["Combustion", "Fermentation", "Oxidation"]}, {"question": "Which ancient civilization used crushed brick in concrete?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Romans", "distractors": ["Greeks", "Egyptians", "Babylonians"]}, {"question": "Brick dust mortar was NOT commonly used in which type of construction?", "type": "negative", "correctAnswer": "Aircraft hangars", "distractors": ["Canal walls", "Harbor foundations", "Bridge piers"]}, {"question": "Brick dust mortar was largely replaced by _____ cement.", "type": "fill_blank", "correctAnswer": "Portland", "distractors": ["Roman", "Egyptian", "Modern"]}, {"question": "Brick dust creates a mortar that can harden underwater.", "type": "true_false", "correctAnswer": "True", "distractors": ["False"]}], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 7, "visualDescription": "A pixel art Roman harbor with underwater mortar setting between stone blocks. Crushed brick particles glow red in the mortar mix. A canal lock and bridge built with brick dust mortar stand strong above.", "ageRating": "kid", "category": "natural_sciences", "contentType": "knowledge", "rarity": "uncommon", "sourceName": "Wikidata", "sourceUrl": "http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q13561156", "sourceRecordId": "http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q13561156", "tags": ["brick-dust", "construction", "material-science", "roman-concrete", "hydraulic-mortar"]}
{"id": "nsci-woodburytype-098", "type": "fact", "statement": "Woodburytype was a photomechanical printing process invented in 1864 that produced the highest quality photographic reproductions of the 19th century.", "explanation": "Walter Bentley Woodbury invented this process which used a lead mold created by a hardened gelatin relief to press pigmented gelatin onto paper. The result was a continuous-tone image with no visible dots or grain — superior to any other printing method of its era. The process was used for book illustrations and portraits until the 1900s.", "wowFactor": "Woodburytype prints from the 1860s have such incredible detail they rival modern photographs!", "quizQuestion": "What made Woodburytype superior to other 19th-century printing methods?", "correctAnswer": "Continuous-tone images with no visible dots", "distractors": [{"text": "It was faster than other methods", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "It used color printing", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "It was cheaper to produce", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "It could print on fabric", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "It was fully automated", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "It used digital technology", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "It required no chemicals", "difficultyTier": "easy"}], "variants": [{"question": "Who invented the Woodburytype process?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Walter Bentley Woodbury", "distractors": ["Louis Daguerre", "William Fox Talbot", "George Eastman"]}, {"question": "What metal was used for the printing mold?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Lead", "distractors": ["Copper", "Steel", "Tin"]}, {"question": "Woodburytype was NOT used for which application?", "type": "negative", "correctAnswer": "Motion pictures", "distractors": ["Book illustrations", "Portraits", "Fine art reproductions"]}, {"question": "Woodburytype was invented in _____.", "type": "fill_blank", "correctAnswer": "1864", "distractors": ["1839", "1888", 