{"id": "nsci-duplex-stainless-steel-099", "type": "fact", "statement": "Duplex stainless steel has a two-phase microstructure of austenite and ferrite, giving it roughly twice the strength of regular stainless steel.", "explanation": "Duplex stainless steels contain roughly equal amounts of austenite and ferrite crystal structures, combining the best properties of both. They resist corrosion better than standard stainless steel, especially in chloride environments. Used in oil rigs, chemical plants, and desalination plants where both strength and corrosion resistance are critical.", "wowFactor": "Duplex steel has TWO crystal structures working together — like having two materials in one!", "quizQuestion": "What two crystal structures does duplex stainless steel contain?", "correctAnswer": "Austenite and ferrite", "distractors": [{"text": "Martensite and pearlite", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "Cementite and graphite", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "Diamond and hexagonal", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "Cubic and tetragonal", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "Bainite and troostite", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "Alpha and beta titanium", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "Zinc and copper phases", "difficultyTier": "easy"}], "variants": [{"question": "How does duplex steel compare to regular stainless steel in strength?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "About twice as strong", "distractors": ["About the same", "Slightly weaker", "Ten times stronger"]}, {"question": "Where is duplex stainless steel commonly used?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Oil rigs and chemical plants", "distractors": ["Kitchen utensils", "Bicycle frames", "Window frames"]}, {"question": "Duplex steel is NOT especially resistant to which type of corrosion?", "type": "negative", "correctAnswer": "High-temperature oxidation above 300°C", "distractors": ["Chloride corrosion", "Stress corrosion cracking", "Pitting corrosion"]}, {"question": "Duplex stainless steel has a _____-phase microstructure.", "type": "fill_blank", "correctAnswer": "Two", "distractors": ["Single", "Three", "Four"]}, {"question": "Duplex stainless steel is used in desalination plants.", "type": "true_false", "correctAnswer": "True", "distractors": ["False"]}], "difficulty": 4, "funScore": 5, "visualDescription": "A pixel art microscope view showing two interleaved crystal structures in blue (austenite) and red (ferrite). An oil rig and chemical plant built with duplex steel stand strong against crashing waves.", "ageRating": "teen", "category": "natural_sciences", "contentType": "knowledge", "rarity": "rare", "sourceName": "Wikidata", "sourceUrl": "http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q1266528", "sourceRecordId": "http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q1266528", "tags": ["duplex-steel", "material-science", "metallurgy", "corrosion-resistance", "engineering"]}
{"id": "nsci-copper-powder-100", "type": "fact", "statement": "Copper powder is finely granulated copper with applications ranging from 3D printing to anti-fouling paints for ship hulls.", "explanation": "Copper powder is produced by atomization (spraying molten copper into gas) or electrolysis. Its excellent thermal and electrical conductivity makes it valuable in powder metallurgy, where metal parts are pressed from powder and sintered. Copper powder in paint prevents barnacles and algae from growing on ship hulls.", "wowFactor": "Ships are painted with copper powder to keep barnacles off — the same trick ancient Greeks used!", "quizQuestion": "How is copper powder commonly produced?", "correctAnswer": "Atomization of molten copper", "distractors": [{"text": "Grinding copper nuggets", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "Chemical vapor deposition", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "Dissolving in acid", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "Laser cutting", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "Freezing and shattering", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "Biological extraction", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "Solar evaporation", "difficultyTier": "easy"}], "variants": [{"question": "Why is copper powder added to ship hull paint?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "To prevent barnacle and algae growth", "distractors": ["To make ships faster", "To prevent rust", "To add color"]}, {"question": "What manufacturing process uses metal powders pressed and heated?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Powder metallurgy", "distractors": ["Casting", "Forging", "Extrusion"]}, {"question": "Copper powder is NOT commonly used in which application?", "type": "negative", "correctAnswer": "Food flavoring", "distractors": ["3D printing", "Anti-fouling paint", "Sintered metal parts"]}, {"question": "Copper powder's conductivity makes it valuable in _____ metallurgy.", "type": "fill_blank", "correctAnswer": "Powder", "distractors": ["Heavy", "Liquid", "Gas"]}, {"question": "Ancient civilizations used copper compounds to prevent barnacle growth on ships.", "type": "true_false", "correctAnswer": "True", "distractors": ["False"]}], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 6, "visualDescription": "A pixel art scene showing copper powder being sprayed from molten metal on the left, a 3D printer using copper powder in the center, and a ship hull being painted with copper anti-fouling paint on the right.", "ageRating": "kid", "category": "natural_sciences", "contentType": "knowledge", "rarity": "uncommon", "sourceName": "Wikidata", "sourceUrl": "http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q91114105", "sourceRecordId": "http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q91114105", "tags": ["copper", "powder-metallurgy", "material-science", "anti-fouling", "3d-printing"]}
{"id": "nsci-photographic-plate-101", "type": "fact", "statement": "Photographic plates are glass plates coated with light-sensitive silver halide emulsion, used to make many of astronomy's greatest discoveries.", "explanation": "Before film, glass photographic plates were the standard medium for photography from the 1850s to the 1990s. Their rigidity made them ideal for astronomical observations because they didn't stretch or warp. Many important discoveries, including the expansion of the universe by Edwin Hubble, were made using photographic plates. Millions of plates in observatory archives are still being digitized.", "wowFactor": "Edwin Hubble discovered the universe is expanding by studying images on glass photographic plates!", "quizQuestion": "Why were photographic plates preferred over film for astronomy?", "correctAnswer": "Glass doesn't stretch or warp like film", "distractors": [{"text": "They were cheaper", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "They produced color images", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "They were lighter", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "They exposed faster", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "They were reusable", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "They were digital", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "They resisted humidity better", "difficultyTier": "hard"}], "variants": [{"question": "What light-sensitive compound coats photographic plates?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Silver halide", "distractors": ["Gold chloride", "Iron oxide", "Platinum sulfide"]}, {"question": "Who used photographic plates to discover the expanding universe?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Edwin Hubble", "distractors": ["Albert Einstein", "Galileo", "Isaac Newton"]}, {"question": "Photographic plates were NOT commonly used for which purpose?", "type": "negative", "correctAnswer": "Motion pictures", "distractors": ["Astronomical surveys", "Medical X-rays", "Spectroscopy"]}, {"question": "Photographic plates were the standard medium from the 1850s to the _____.", "type": "fill_blank", "correctAnswer": "1990s", "distractors": ["1920s", "1950s", "2010s"]}, {"question": "Millions of photographic plates from observatories are still being digitized.", "type": "true_false", "correctAnswer": "True", "distractors": ["False"]}], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 7, "visualDescription": "A pixel art observatory dome with a telescope pointed at the stars. Glass photographic plates show spiral galaxies and star fields. Edwin Hubble examines a plate with a magnifying glass at a desk.", "ageRating": "kid", "category": "natural_sciences", "contentType": "knowledge", "rarity": "uncommon", "sourceName": "Wikidata", "sourceUrl": "http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q1138868", "sourceRecordId": "http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q1138868", "tags": ["photographic-plate", "photography", "astronomy", "hubble", "glass"]}
{"id": "nsci-thermoplastic-polyurethane-102", "type": "fact", "statement": "Thermoplastic polyurethane (TPU) is a versatile elastic polymer used in phone cases, shoe soles, and medical devices.", "explanation": "TPU combines the elasticity of rubber with the processability of plastic — it can be melted and reformed repeatedly without losing its properties. It is resistant to oil, grease, and abrasion, making it ideal for protective cases and industrial applications. TPU is also used in 3D printing to create flexible parts.", "wowFactor": "TPU can be melted and reshaped endlessly without wearing out — the ultimate recyclable plastic!", "quizQuestion": "What unique property distinguishes TPU from regular rubber?", "correctAnswer": "It can be melted and reformed repeatedly", "distractors": [{"text": "It's stronger than steel", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "It's transparent", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "It conducts electricity", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "It dissolves in water", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "It's lighter than air", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "It's naturally occurring", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "It glows in UV light", "difficultyTier": "medium"}], "variants": [{"question": "What does TPU stand for?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Thermoplastic polyurethane", "distractors": ["Thermal polymer unit", "Tough plastic universal", "Transparent polyester unit"]}, {"question": "Which product commonly uses TPU?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Phone cases", "distractors": ["Window glass", "Paper", "Cotton clothing"]}, {"question": "TPU is NOT resistant to which substance?", "type": "negative", "correctAnswer": "Strong acids", "distractors": ["Oil", "Grease", "Abrasion"]}, {"question": "TPU combines the elasticity of rubber with the processability of _____.", "type": "fill_blank", "correctAnswer": "Plastic", "distractors": ["Metal", "Glass", "Ceramic"]}, {"question": "TPU is used in 3D printing to create flexible parts.", "type": "true_false", "correctAnswer": "True", "distractors": ["False"]}], "difficulty": 2, "funScore": 6, "visualDescription": "A pixel art scene showing TPU being extruded from a 3D printer into a flexible phone case shape. Shoe soles and medical tubing made of TPU are displayed. The material stretches and bounces back.", "ageRating": "kid", "category": "natural_sciences", "contentType": "knowledge", "rarity": "common", "sourceName": "Wikidata", "sourceUrl": "http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q7783228", "sourceRecordId": "http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q7783228", "tags": ["tpu", "polymer", "material-science", "3d-printing", "elastomer"]}
{"id": "nsci-photographic-plate-glass-103", "type": "fact", "statement": "Photosensitive materials are substances that change their physical or chemical properties when exposed to light, forming the basis of photography.", "explanation": "Photosensitive materials include silver halides (used in traditional photography), photoresists (used in semiconductor manufacturing), and photochromic compounds (used in self-darkening sunglasses). The discovery that silver compounds darken in light, made in 1727 by Johann Heinrich Schulze, eventually led to the invention of photography over a century later.", "wowFactor": "The discovery that silver darkens in sunlight in 1727 took over 100 years to become photography!", "quizQuestion": "Who first discovered that silver compounds darken when exposed to light?", "correctAnswer": "Johann Heinrich Schulze", "distractors": [{"text": "Louis Daguerre", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "Joseph Niépce", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "William Fox Talbot", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "George Eastman", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "Thomas Edison", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "Alexander Graham Bell", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "Isaac Newton", "difficultyTier": "easy"}], "variants": [{"question": "What type of material is used in self-darkening sunglasses?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Photochromic compounds", "distractors": ["Photovoltaic cells", "Thermochromic paint", "Electrochromic glass"]}, {"question": "Photoresists are photosensitive materials used in which industry?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Semiconductor manufacturing", "distractors": ["Food processing", "Textile weaving", "Automotive painting"]}, {"question": "Photosensitive materials do NOT rely on which mechanism?", "type": "negative", "correctAnswer": "Magnetic field changes", "distractors": ["Chemical reactions with light", "Physical property changes", "Electron excitation"]}, {"question": "Silver halides darken when exposed to _____.", "type": "fill_blank", "correctAnswer": "Light", "distractors": ["Heat", "Water", "Air"]}, {"question": "Photosensitive materials are the basis of modern photography.", "type": "true_false", "correctAnswer": "True", "distractors": ["False"]}], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 6, "visualDescription": "A pixel art timeline showing silver darkening in sunlight (1727), a daguerreotype camera (1839), and modern photochromic sunglasses darkening in sunlight. Light beams hit each material causing visible changes.", "ageRating": "kid", "category": "natural_sciences", "contentType": "knowledge", "rarity": "uncommon", "sourceName": "Wikidata", "sourceUrl": "http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q4410572", "sourceRecordId": "http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q4410572", "tags": ["photosensitive", "photography", "material-science", "silver-halide", "optics"]}
{"id": "nsci-vulcanized-fibre-104", "type": "fact", "statement": "Vulcanized fibre is a laminated material made by treating cellulose with zinc chloride, creating a tough, lightweight, spark-resistant material.", "explanation": "Despite its name, vulcanized fibre contains no rubber — the 'vulcanized' refers to its toughening process. It has been used since the 1860s for electrical insulation, luggage, and even body armor. Vulcanized fibre is still used today in washers, gaskets, and electrical components because it is self-extinguishing and does not produce sparks.", "wowFactor": "Vulcanized fibre has nothing to do with rubber — and it was used as body armor in the Civil War era!", "quizQuestion": "What chemical is used to treat cellulose in making vulcanized fibre?", "correctAnswer": "Zinc chloride", "distractors": [{"text": "Sulfuric acid", "difficultyTier": "hard"}, {"text": "Sodium hydroxide", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "Hydrochloric acid", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "Calcium carbonate", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "Iron oxide", "difficultyTier": "easy"}, {"text": "Copper sulfate", "difficultyTier": "medium"}, {"text": "Potassium nitrate", "difficultyTier": "hard"}], "variants": [{"question": "Why is vulcanized fibre used in electrical applications?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "It is spark-resistant and self-extinguishing", "distractors": ["It conducts electricity well", "It is magnetic", "It is transparent"]}, {"question": "What is vulcanized fibre NOT made from?", "type": "negative", "correctAnswer": "Rubber", "distractors": ["Cellulose", "Paper layers", "Zinc chloride solution"]}, {"question": "Vulcanized fibre has been used since the _____.", "type": "fill_blank", "correctAnswer": "1860s", "distractors": ["1920s", "1780s", "1950s"]}, {"question": "What base material is vulcanized fibre made from?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Cellulose", "distractors": ["Polymer resin", "Metal foil", "Glass fiber"]}, {"questio